00:04:49.186 --> 00:04:50.996
But what was so special

00:04:51.196 --> 00:04:52.146
about these stories?

00:04:52.396 --> 00:04:54.546
And how did they get so popular?

00:04:55.906 --> 00:04:58.476
Well, as the name suggests, penny

00:04:58.486 --> 00:05:01.526
dreadfuls were sold for a single penny.

00:05:02.406 --> 00:05:05.186
Sure, a penny back in the 19th century

00:05:05.196 --> 00:05:07.176
was worth a lot more than it is

00:05:07.176 --> 00:05:09.716
today, but it was still very cheap.

00:05:10.616 --> 00:05:14.106
One penny is about 25p now, it's

00:05:14.226 --> 00:05:16.806
a quarter of a pound, but perhaps

00:05:16.826 --> 00:05:19.366
a better comparison is that one

00:05:19.556 --> 00:05:21.696
instalment of these books was about

00:05:21.696 --> 00:05:24.046
the same price as a loaf of bread.

00:05:25.316 --> 00:05:27.206
And to give you another point of

00:05:27.206 --> 00:05:29.946
comparison, this genre was very

00:05:29.946 --> 00:05:32.386
cheap compared to normal books,

00:05:32.446 --> 00:05:34.206
books you may well have heard of.

00:05:35.466 --> 00:05:38.086
For example, an instalment of a Charles

00:05:38.086 --> 00:05:40.846
Dickens novel such as Oliver Twist would

00:05:40.846 --> 00:05:43.976
cost around 12 pennies, or 1 shilling.

00:05:45.286 --> 00:05:47.026
Before you’re thinking, hang on,

00:05:47.256 --> 00:05:49.326
these Penny Dreadfuls are just short

00:05:49.326 --> 00:05:51.846
stories or chapters of a book, no

00:05:51.846 --> 00:05:54.066
wonder Oliver Twist was more expensive,

00:05:54.356 --> 00:05:56.974
it's an entire book, remember that

00:05:56.974 --> 00:05:59.004
Charles Dickens also published

00:05:59.004 --> 00:06:01.364
his books in the same, serialised,

00:06:01.364 --> 00:06:03.924
format, with new instalments coming

00:06:03.924 --> 00:06:06.204
out over a period of weeks or months.

00:06:07.074 --> 00:06:09.944
So, each instalment of a Penny Dreadful

00:06:09.954 --> 00:06:12.774
was incredibly cheap, less than

00:06:12.774 --> 00:06:15.329
1/10th of the cost of a normal book.

00:06:16.757 --> 00:06:20.154
As you might expect, this low price tag

00:06:20.304 --> 00:06:22.854
did a great deal to expand the number

00:06:22.854 --> 00:06:25.554
of people who were able to read or, if

00:06:25.554 --> 00:06:27.524
they were illiterate, listen to these

00:06:27.524 --> 00:06:30.674
stories, and in so doing for the first

00:06:30.684 --> 00:06:33.894
time it opened up literature to society’s

00:06:33.974 --> 00:06:36.424
poorest, which in Victorian England,

00:06:36.434 --> 00:06:38.594
was the majority of the population.

00:06:39.484 --> 00:06:41.254
So, how was it possible

00:06:41.404 --> 00:06:42.514
to make them so cheap?

00:06:43.384 --> 00:06:45.177
Well, partly, automation.

00:06:46.140 --> 00:06:48.055
Innovations in printing technology

00:06:48.295 --> 00:06:50.215
allowed for mass produced prints

00:06:50.235 --> 00:06:52.515
on very cheap and thin paper.

00:06:53.665 --> 00:06:55.205
With the invention of the steam

00:06:55.205 --> 00:06:58.605
powered press in 1814, printing had

00:06:58.605 --> 00:07:00.925
become mechanical and automated.

00:07:01.675 --> 00:07:04.775
It was 5 times faster than the at-the-time

00:07:04.775 --> 00:07:07.075
revolutionary Gutenberg printing press.

00:07:07.765 --> 00:07:10.325
Paper was cheap, for once, and the

00:07:10.325 --> 00:07:12.475
process of printing onto the paper,

00:07:12.735 --> 00:07:14.325
and then putting it all together,

00:07:14.405 --> 00:07:16.721
was more efficient than ever before.

00:07:17.671 --> 00:07:20.051
To keep costs low, they did not

00:07:20.061 --> 00:07:22.851
have fancy thick book covers,

00:07:23.011 --> 00:07:25.671
they were simply 8 to 16 pages of

00:07:25.861 --> 00:07:28.051
thin paper with columns of text.

00:07:28.861 --> 00:07:30.471
Really, they were more like a

00:07:30.631 --> 00:07:33.291
modern-day magazine or comic book.

00:07:34.251 --> 00:07:35.991
And let’s not forget the cost

00:07:35.991 --> 00:07:38.271
of actually writing the stories.

00:07:39.361 --> 00:07:42.061
This genre, much like what is

00:07:42.251 --> 00:07:44.871
disparagingly called “airport novels”

00:07:45.121 --> 00:07:48.091
nowadays, was written quickly, often

00:07:48.091 --> 00:07:51.281
with generic and formulaic characters.

00:07:52.101 --> 00:07:53.981
Authors working for publishing houses

00:07:53.981 --> 00:07:56.881
would write tirelessly, often being paid

00:07:57.061 --> 00:08:00.081
a penny per line and being responsible

00:08:00.101 --> 00:08:03.011
for up to 10 stories at the same time.

00:08:04.221 --> 00:08:06.371
As a result, Penny Dreadfuls

00:08:06.371 --> 00:08:08.071
were criticised for their lack

00:08:08.131 --> 00:08:10.011
of literary merit, for not

00:08:10.031 --> 00:08:11.771
being particularly good books.

00:08:12.821 --> 00:08:14.991
We’ll come to some of the results of

00:08:14.991 --> 00:08:17.381
this shortly, but the point to remember

00:08:17.381 --> 00:08:19.451
here is that they were very cheap

00:08:19.461 --> 00:08:21.341
to make, meaning that they could be

00:08:21.341 --> 00:08:23.466
sold for the cost of a loaf of bread.

00:08:24.706 --> 00:08:26.536
And the result of these penny

00:08:26.536 --> 00:08:28.756
dreadfuls being so affordable was,

00:08:29.086 --> 00:08:30.766
of course, that they could be bought

00:08:30.926 --> 00:08:33.176
and enjoyed by people who would never

00:08:33.336 --> 00:08:35.076
have been able to buy a book before.

00:08:36.176 --> 00:08:39.026
The 19th century was, after all, a time

00:08:39.046 --> 00:08:41.426
of booming literacy rates in Britain,

00:08:41.816 --> 00:08:43.506
principally due to the widespread

00:08:43.546 --> 00:08:45.796
availability of schooling for children.

00:08:47.086 --> 00:08:51.056
In the 1830s, under 50% of women and

00:08:51.416 --> 00:08:53.966
only around 60% of men could read.

00:08:54.996 --> 00:08:58.746
Within just 40 years, by the mid 1870s,

00:08:59.366 --> 00:09:02.596
90% of the British population could read.

00:09:03.706 --> 00:09:06.316
And despite these better education

00:09:06.356 --> 00:09:08.466
outcomes for children, as you may

00:09:08.466 --> 00:09:10.906
know, life in Victorian Britain was

00:09:11.106 --> 00:09:14.136
pretty tough and miserable, especially

00:09:14.216 --> 00:09:16.186
at the start of the 19th century.

00:09:17.226 --> 00:09:21.236
In 1821, almost half of the entire

00:09:21.246 --> 00:09:24.276
workforce was under the age of 20

00:09:24.736 --> 00:09:27.176
and the average age children began

00:09:27.186 --> 00:09:29.456
working was just 10 years old.

00:09:30.476 --> 00:09:32.606
They would work in factories, on

00:09:32.606 --> 00:09:35.376
farms, as chimney sweeps, in all

00:09:35.376 --> 00:09:37.896
manner of tough and dangerous jobs.

00:09:39.076 --> 00:09:41.276
Even Charles Dickens, who became the

00:09:41.276 --> 00:09:43.626
most celebrated and successful of

00:09:43.626 --> 00:09:46.016
Victorian writers, worked as a child

00:09:46.166 --> 00:09:48.686
in a factory that produced boot polish.

00:09:49.876 --> 00:09:51.766
Throughout the 19th century, the

00:09:51.846 --> 00:09:54.686
British government did pass legislation

00:09:54.706 --> 00:09:56.966
to improve the plight of the working

00:09:56.976 --> 00:09:59.306
poor, but it was a slow process.

00:10:00.286 --> 00:10:03.716
In 1833, for example, the “Factory

00:10:03.716 --> 00:10:06.506
Act'' was celebrated as a wonderful

00:10:06.506 --> 00:10:09.426
thing for children, but what did it say?

00:10:10.046 --> 00:10:11.906
Only that you had to be 9

00:10:11.916 --> 00:10:13.666
years old to legally work.

00:10:14.666 --> 00:10:17.416
In any case, even if it did improve,

00:10:17.566 --> 00:10:20.606
slightly, life as a child in Victorian

00:10:20.606 --> 00:10:22.456
Britain was somewhat miserable.

00:10:22.942 --> 00:10:26.133
And suddenly, along came this option

00:10:26.153 --> 00:10:28.273
of reading stories of adventure,

00:10:28.693 --> 00:10:31.333
mystery, murder, and the supernatural,

00:10:31.743 --> 00:10:33.583
all at a price that wouldn’t break the

00:10:33.583 --> 00:10:35.415
bank, that you could actually afford.

00:10:37.085 --> 00:10:40.295
As such, these books provided a welcome

00:10:40.295 --> 00:10:43.385
escape from the drudgery, boredom and

00:10:43.545 --> 00:10:46.115
hardship of factory life or classroom

00:10:46.115 --> 00:10:49.085
learning, and they were a massive hit.

00:10:50.215 --> 00:10:52.395
So, you are probably wondering, what

00:10:52.425 --> 00:10:54.375
were these stories actually about?

00:10:55.355 --> 00:10:57.585
Well, you heard a bit of one at the

00:10:57.585 --> 00:10:59.675
